{"term":"2012","caseName":"Vance v. Ball State University","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/11-556","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - November 26, 2012","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22509","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument next this morning in Case 11-556, Vance v. Ball State University.","start":0,"stop":9.356,"duration":9.36},{"text":"Mr. Ortiz.","start":9.356,"stop":10.272,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":10.272,"stop":12.308,"duration":2.04},{"text":"This case concerns who counts and who does not count as a supervisor under Title VII.","start":12.308,"stop":17.276,"duration":4.97},{"text":"The parties and the United States agree that the Seventh Circuit rule violates the holding of Faragher, the reasoning of Faragher and this Court's other central Title VII precedents, including Burlington Northern and Staub, and the common-sense meaning of the word “ supervisor ”.","start":17.276,"stop":30.935,"duration":13.66},{"text":"The parties even agree as to the general legal standard, although they style it a little bit different -- differently, that those harassers whose employer-conferred authority over their victims enables or materially augments the harassment should count as supervisors.","start":30.935,"stop":47.045,"duration":16.11},{"text":"This is not a standard, Your Honor, that imposes automatic liability on employers.","start":47.045,"stop":52.283,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Victims must still prove actionable harassment, and employers can still take advantage of the Ellerth/Faragher affirmative defense.","start":52.283,"stop":59.455,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's say you have a work room.","start":59.455,"stop":62.573,"duration":3.12},{"text":"There are five people who work there.","start":62.573,"stop":63.89,"duration":1.32},{"text":"And the employer has a rule that the senior employee gets to pick the music that's going to play all day long.","start":63.89,"stop":72.679,"duration":8.79},{"text":"And the senior employee says to one of the other employees, you know, if you don't date me -- I know you don't like country music; if you don't date me, it's going to be country music all day long.","start":72.679,"stop":83.404,"duration":10.72},{"text":"Now, that affects the daily activities of that other employee.","start":83.404,"stop":89.241,"duration":5.84},{"text":"I would have thought, under your theory, that means that that senior employee is a supervisor.","start":89.241,"stop":94.795,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, because in that circumstance the adverse action would not amount to -- would not be severe.","start":94.795,"stop":104.317,"duration":9.52},{"text":"Or, perhaps it would be pervasive--","start":104.317,"stop":106.519,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that could be -- that could be far more severe than, for example--","start":106.519,"stop":110.137,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Hard rock instead of--","start":110.137,"stop":111.621,"duration":1.48},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":111.621,"stop":112.173,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--It could be far more severe than simply saying, all right, you know, you're going to -- as in this case -- you're going to be cutting the celery rather than, you know, baking the bread, or whatever.","start":112.173,"stop":122.695,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, no, Your Honor, this is the -- the severity is an objective standard; it's not a subjective.","start":122.695,"stop":127.449,"duration":4.75},{"text":"So in this case, someone's intense dislike -- maybe it's debilitating, subjective -- dislike of rock music, some forms of country music -- might impair the performance of some in the workplace; but, from an objective reasonable employee's standpoint, I don't believe that that would be the case.","start":127.449,"stop":148.096,"duration":20.65},{"text":"Not all--","start":148.096,"stop":148.512,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but, I mean, there are places where the environment -- you know, an assembly line or something like that -- where the task may not be that different, but how you -- the environment in which you have to perform them may be far more significant than whether or not you're attaching the door handles or the front fenders.","start":148.512,"stop":163.939,"duration":15.43}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, for sure, Your Honor, but they have to be judged on a case-by-case basis.","start":163.939,"stop":167.408,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, exactly.","start":167.408,"stop":167.924,"duration":0.52},{"text":"And I would have thought the benefit of the Seventh Circuit's test was that you don't have to go through those case-by-case basis.","start":167.924,"stop":175.097,"duration":7.17},{"text":"I think we can have a reasonable debate about whether the music you have to listen to for eight hours is objectively a significant enough interference with the daily activities to qualify under your test.","start":175.097,"stop":186.054,"duration":10.96},{"text":"But the Seventh Circuit test makes clear -- it doesn't give any kind of immunity; it just makes clear what type of analysis is going to be applied to the allegation.","start":186.054,"stop":195.41,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the Respondent actually exaggerates the determinativeness of the Seventh Circuit rule, and the indeterminativeness -- both indeterminativeness and unpredictability of the Second Circuit rule.","start":195.41,"stop":206.885,"duration":11.47},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit itself has recognized -- the judges in the Seventh Circuit itself have recognized that the rule does not really well fit the realities of the workplace.","start":206.885,"stop":215.657,"duration":8.77},{"text":"It also just moves uncertainty from one category to another.","start":215.657,"stop":219.776,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The category of supervisor may be a little bit tidier; but, under the Seventh Circuit's approach, the category of co-worker is very unpredictable.","start":219.776,"stop":230.064,"duration":10.29},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit itself, in Doe v. Oberweis Dairy, recognized that once you move people who can take -- have this kind of power over their victims but can't actually take annual employment actions against them into the category of co-workers, all of a sudden you have to apply a sliding scale of negligence.","start":230.064,"stop":250.062,"duration":20},{"text":"Not only that, but the jury is the one who applies it.","start":250.062,"stop":252.664,"duration":2.6},{"text":"So for those categories -- this exact category of employee, Your Honor, the employer going forward has very little idea of whether -- what standard of care is that a particular jury would apply in that case and whether the jury would decide it is met or not.","start":252.664,"stop":270.958,"duration":18.29},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit rule, in the overall, is no more determinative than the Second Circuit rule.","start":270.958,"stop":276.529,"duration":5.57},{"text":"Also, Respondent points to no cases in the Second Circuit or the other circuits that have adopted this rule where courts have identified problems with its application.","start":276.529,"stop":286.985,"duration":10.46},{"text":"And that--","start":286.985,"stop":287.685,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could you point out what the materially augments rule means?","start":287.685,"stop":290.92,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Could you provide a definition of that?","start":290.92,"stop":293.955,"duration":3.03},{"text":"The authority to assign daily tasks has to be sufficient to do what?","start":293.955,"stop":300.895,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--It has to be sufficient to enable the harasser to instill either fear in the victim that the victim should not turn the harasser in, or that it may have to do with the harasser's ability to control the physical location of the victim.","start":300.895,"stop":326.176,"duration":25.28},{"text":"That can augment harassment.","start":326.176,"stop":328.128,"duration":1.95},{"text":"If an harasser can steer a victim to a location where the harasser has an opportunity to harass, and, indeed, may have an opportunity to harass without other employees or other people in the company seeing in, that would materially augment--","start":328.128,"stop":345.024,"duration":16.9}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There are situations where the assignment of responsibilities is extremely unpleasant, and so it's easy to see how the testimony would apply in that situation.","start":345.024,"stop":356.129,"duration":11.11},{"text":"But there are also a lot of situations, like the Chief Justice's example, where it's really very unclear.","start":356.129,"stop":361.949,"duration":5.82},{"text":"I don't know how courts are going to -- how courts can grapple with that.","start":361.949,"stop":365.42,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, this--","start":365.42,"stop":367.337,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You said that being subjected to country music or hard rock or Wagner, you know, every single day in the workplace would not be sufficient.","start":367.337,"stop":376.709,"duration":9.37},{"text":"I don't know.","start":376.709,"stop":377.145,"duration":0.44},{"text":"Some people might think that it was -- that that is.","start":377.145,"stop":380.93,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Alito, this part of the standard, particularly the materiality requirement, is meant to track this Court's standard in Burlington Northern, where it said that only actions that are materially adverse to the employee would count.","start":380.93,"stop":394.32,"duration":13.39},{"text":"And this Court identified the materiality requirement there as actually working to make the standard more objective, not--","start":394.32,"stop":402.509,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ortiz, why isn't the question that you're presenting academic in this case?","start":402.509,"stop":407.58,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Because didn't the district judge say that there had been no showing that Davis' conduct was sufficiently severe or pervasive?","start":407.58,"stop":420.971,"duration":13.39},{"text":"It wouldn't matter if the supervisor -- if the conduct was not sufficiently severe or pervasive harassment, and, equally, if the company responded every time a complaint was lodged.","start":420.971,"stop":438.932,"duration":17.96},{"text":"The district court found both of those things, that it wasn't severe and pervasive, and that every time she complained an investigation was made.","start":438.932,"stop":449.49,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Ginsburg, we actually tried to bring those things up before the Seventh Circuit, but the Seventh Circuit found it unnecessary to reach them because of its holding as to supervisory liability.","start":449.49,"stop":461.132,"duration":11.64},{"text":"If this Court were to reverse the Seventh Circuit's affirmance of summary judgment of the district court, the case would then be remanded to the Seventh Circuit, where it could either look at these alternative -- these other holdings, or the thing would be -- it could be remanded at that point and sent back to the district court for another look.","start":461.132,"stop":481.51,"duration":20.38},{"text":"The district court's reasoning, the Seventh Circuit noted, when it was talking about other incidents of harassment was very unusual.","start":481.51,"stop":490.817,"duration":9.31},{"text":"What the district court did was it divided all of the incidents into two categories.","start":490.817,"stop":497.905,"duration":7.09},{"text":"One category -- one category consisted of events that by themselves were not overtly racial in nature and the other category consisted of those events that were overtly racial in nature, where a racial epithet had been hurled at someone, for example, and said with respect to the first category, the things -- the events that on their face did not announce racial animosity, that there wasn't any racial nexus, so they didn't count, and swept all those events out and then looked at the remaining ones where the connection to racial animus was overt.","start":497.905,"stop":536.013,"duration":38.11},{"text":"And it said, well, these, there may be some, but they just don't count.","start":536.013,"stop":540.548,"duration":4.53},{"text":"So the Seventh Circuit itself discredited the reasoning of the district court in those very holdings.","start":540.548,"stop":547.154,"duration":6.61}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ortiz, suppose I agree with your standard, but I just can't find on the record as it has been presented in this Court any evidence that Davis actually served as Vance's supervisor.","start":547.154,"stop":562.414,"duration":15.26},{"text":"What -- I mean, what's your best -- so if that's true, I would be tempted to actually just decide the thing rather than to remand it.","start":562.414,"stop":572.869,"duration":10.46},{"text":"So as against that approach, what is your best evidence that there was a supervisory relationship under your standard here?","start":572.869,"stop":581.709,"duration":8.84}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"First, Justice Kagan, it is important to keep in mind that the record was developed under the wrong legal standard.","start":581.709,"stop":587.279,"duration":5.57},{"text":"But even considering that--","start":587.279,"stop":588.498,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that the case?","start":588.498,"stop":588.998,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Is there evidence that you did not present because the Seventh Circuit applied a different standard?","start":588.998,"stop":594.819,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--There was evidence that was probably not developed below because the Seventh Circuit's standard was so absolute.","start":594.819,"stop":603.074,"duration":8.25},{"text":"But there is actually evidence in the record, we believe plenty of evidence, sufficient certainly to overcome summary judgment, although perhaps not enough for partial summary judgment on this question in our favor.","start":603.074,"stop":615.632,"duration":12.56}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What other than the job description?","start":615.632,"stop":617.148,"duration":1.52},{"text":"The job description says that the catering specialist has authority to direct or lead the part-time employees.","start":617.148,"stop":627.523,"duration":10.38},{"text":"But what concrete instances of Davis exercising supervisory authority over Vance is there in this record?","start":627.523,"stop":639.831,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice -- there is two separate questions, Justice Ginsburg.","start":639.831,"stop":643.116,"duration":3.28},{"text":"One is instances of it; others is whether she has the authority or not.","start":643.116,"stop":647.353,"duration":4.24},{"text":"Because this Court has held in Faragher itself that it is the authority that makes the difference, not the actual exercising of it in a particular case.","start":647.353,"stop":654.09,"duration":6.74},{"text":"But let me go through what is in the record now, much of it which is in the Joint Appendix but not all, because we were not aware that we would be opposing a summary judgment motion before this Court.","start":654.09,"stop":664.029,"duration":9.94},{"text":"First, William Kimes, who is the director of the university banquet and catering division, thus the head of this 60-some-person department.","start":664.029,"stop":674.271,"duration":10.24},{"text":"Two employees testified that he told them that Davis was a supervisor.","start":674.271,"stop":679.056,"duration":4.79},{"text":"One of them was Vance; that could be found on page 198 of the Joint Appendix.","start":679.056,"stop":683.11,"duration":4.05},{"text":"Another is an employee who was in Vance's position named Dawn Knox, and that statement can be found on page 386 of the Joint Appendix.","start":683.11,"stop":689.846,"duration":6.74},{"text":"William Kimes himself testified in his deposition that Davis, quote:","start":689.846,"stop":694.215,"duration":4.37},{"text":"\"Directed and led other employees in the kitchen. \"","start":694.215,"stop":696.634,"duration":2.42},{"text":"That can be found on page 367 of the Joint Appendix.","start":696.634,"stop":700.036,"duration":3.4},{"text":"In an internal investigation by compliance officers at Ball State--","start":700.036,"stop":705.373,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What I mean is not the statement, well, she's a supervisor.","start":705.373,"stop":709.26,"duration":3.89},{"text":"But comparable to Faragher, where the lifeguard who didn't have authority to hire her or fire her said, if you don't date me, you are going to be cleaning the toilets.","start":709.26,"stop":720.616,"duration":11.36},{"text":"We don't have anything like that in this record.","start":720.616,"stop":724.02,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, there was no overt threat like that in the record, but the person who was hurling racial epithets at her was in a position of authority over her, both according to the job description, also according to her understanding, according--","start":724.02,"stop":740.863,"duration":16.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was also -- that would be for a very confined period.","start":740.863,"stop":743.665,"duration":2.8},{"text":"It would only be when the -- when Vance was a part-time employee.","start":743.665,"stop":748.735,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Once she is a full-time employee there isn't that.","start":748.735,"stop":752.604,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Your Honor.","start":752.604,"stop":753.539,"duration":0.93},{"text":"There is two separate provisions in the job description which cover the whole period of time here.","start":753.539,"stop":757.425,"duration":3.89},{"text":"The harassment started around September 2005, went in through August -- went to August 2007 with one incident, March 1st, I believe it was, 2008.","start":757.425,"stop":770.965,"duration":13.54},{"text":"On January 1st, 2007, Ms. Vance received a promotion from part-time to full-time.","start":770.965,"stop":777.404,"duration":6.44},{"text":"Page 13 on the Joint Appendix has this item that you pointed to, Justice, which specifically lists among the duties and responsibilities of the catering specialist leading and directing part-time employees.","start":777.404,"stop":790.712,"duration":13.31},{"text":"However, page 12 of the Joint Appendix lists under positions supervised by the catering specialist, exactly Vance's position.","start":790.712,"stop":800.651,"duration":9.94},{"text":"So when she moved from full-time -- sorry, from part-time to full-time in January 2007, the supervisory nexus in the job description merely jumped from page 13 to page 12.","start":800.651,"stop":811.625,"duration":10.97},{"text":"But it was covered for that whole period of time.","start":811.625,"stop":814.76,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the most unpleasant thing that Davis could have assigned the Petitioner to do?","start":814.76,"stop":820.314,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Could it be chopping onions all day, every day?","start":820.314,"stop":824.116,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly within the -- within the job duties that she traditionally did, the kind of things she had to work with, what she had to do, things like this, working with onions, chopping onions all day might be punishment.","start":824.116,"stop":841.728,"duration":17.61},{"text":"Unfortunately again, though, the record wasn't developed under an understanding that all of this would be irrelevant.","start":841.728,"stop":847.799,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that would materially augment?","start":847.799,"stop":849.416,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Chopping onions all day would be enough?","start":849.416,"stop":851.033,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":851.033,"stop":852.485,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Chopping -- how about chopping other things, just chopping?","start":852.485,"stop":855.32,"duration":2.84},{"text":"You are the sous-chef, you are going to be chopping all day every day.","start":855.32,"stop":858.606,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Would that be enough?","start":858.606,"stop":859.572,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Possibly, Your Honor.","start":859.572,"stop":860.488,"duration":0.92},{"text":"It depends, again, on questions which would depend upon how you had to chop, how heavy the knives were, whether you would get repetitive injuries.","start":860.488,"stop":868.309,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ortiz, did she ever have that authority, because the record as far as we have it says that the work assignment, what Vance was doing, came from the chef or from Kimes, and the most that Davis did was transmit the chef's orders of where people would be stationed.","start":868.309,"stop":892.959,"duration":24.65}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it is not quite clear at this point.","start":892.959,"stop":896.911,"duration":3.95},{"text":"Vance, in an internal investigation at Ball State University, Ms. Vance told the compliance officer who was conducting the investigation that Davis delegated jobs to her in the kitchen.","start":896.911,"stop":913.207,"duration":16.3},{"text":"That appears in Document 59-16 on page 2.","start":913.207,"stop":917.092,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, may I interrupt a moment on--","start":917.092,"stop":919.694,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":919.694,"stop":920.494,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--following up on an issue raised in part by the Chief and by Justice Ginsburg.","start":920.494,"stop":925.097,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Assuming that Davis was a direct supervisor, would there be an affirmative defense available to the employer?","start":925.097,"stop":938.588,"duration":13.49}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"For sure, Your -- for sure, Your Honor.","start":938.588,"stop":940.274,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be your position?","start":940.274,"stop":941.474,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":941.474,"stop":942.226,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That this could not be grounds that someone who directs an employee's day-to-day activity should be treated like someone who hasn't actually undertaken the threat because the situations are different.","start":942.226,"stop":961.538,"duration":19.31}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":961.538,"stop":962.738,"duration":1.2},{"text":"This is -- this falls out of the structure of the affirmative defense as laid out in Ellerth and Faragher.","start":962.738,"stop":968.007,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what this fight is about?","start":968.007,"stop":968.876,"duration":0.87},{"text":"What if we were to say that the EEOC's test governed or the Second Circuit test governed, but because of the nature of the difference between formal supervisors who take tangible work activities and informal supervisors who the employer would have less control over and less knowledge about their activities, that we would require an employee to complain.","start":968.876,"stop":999.313,"duration":30.44},{"text":"Would that be a crazy rule, and why?","start":999.313,"stop":1002.347,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"That this Court would require under those circumstances?","start":1002.347,"stop":1006.216,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Would require, would permit the affirmative defense to be raised by an employer.","start":1006.216,"stop":1012.453,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't actually map on well to the structure of the affirmative defenses laid out in Ellerth and Faragher.","start":1012.453,"stop":1021.309,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but there is a difference between those supervisors who take direct activity, tangible direct actions, who are in power to do that, and supervisors who don't have that power, because supervisors who don't have that power are supervised -- their actions are supervised in a way that non-tangible employment supervisors are not.","start":1021.309,"stop":1049.578,"duration":28.27}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the existing affirmative -- affirmative defense, as I understand it, Your Honor, an employee who doesn't complain, unless they are reasonable in not complaining, in most cases would make the affirmative defense unavailable to the employer.","start":1049.578,"stop":1069.659,"duration":20.08},{"text":"Is it the question concerning the difference between unreasonably failing to complain--","start":1069.659,"stop":1075.229,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's whether, whether or not this whole fight is over that issue.","start":1075.229,"stop":1078.848,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--That -- this whole -- the fight is in -- in part about that issue.","start":1078.848,"stop":1084.251,"duration":5.4},{"text":"That is certainly not the only--","start":1084.251,"stop":1085.684,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because it's also about the burden of proof.","start":1085.684,"stop":1088.119,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1088.119,"stop":1088.353,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So if we keep the burden of proof with respect to the employer raising the affirmative defense, does that solve half your problem?","start":1088.353,"stop":1100.011,"duration":11.66}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1100.011,"stop":1100.861,"duration":0.85},{"text":"It makes it better.","start":1100.861,"stop":1102.713,"duration":1.85},{"text":"And this Court has recognized the affirmative defense appropriately allocates the burdens between the employee and the employer going forward.","start":1102.713,"stop":1113.501,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Your Honor, the Seventh Circuit rule, although unsupported by Respondent, is supported by several of the Respondents' amici.","start":1113.501,"stop":1123.559,"duration":10.06},{"text":"As I said, they tend to oversell the determinativeness of the Seventh Circuit rule.","start":1123.559,"stop":1128.78,"duration":5.22},{"text":"They exaggerate the -- the uncertainties that they predict will happen under the--","start":1128.78,"stop":1137.719,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you tell me what you see as the major difference between the EEOC and the Second Circuit rule, and why one is compelled over the other?","start":1137.719,"stop":1146.372,"duration":8.65},{"text":"It's the regulatory agency charged with oversight of -- of the implementation of the statute.","start":1146.372,"stop":1155.061,"duration":8.69},{"text":"Why shouldn't we give deference to it on--","start":1155.061,"stop":1157.763,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor--","start":1157.763,"stop":1159.465,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--the standard it sets forth?","start":1159.465,"stop":1161.049,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--it is -- it is entitled to deference under Skidmore, no more.","start":1161.049,"stop":1164.417,"duration":3.37},{"text":"And it is our understanding, although the government--","start":1164.417,"stop":1169.719,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":1169.719,"stop":1170.671,"duration":0.95},{"text":"Why -- why -- why no more?","start":1170.671,"stop":1172.105,"duration":1.43},{"text":"Why just Skidmore?","start":1172.105,"stop":1173.273,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because it's -- it's only informal guidance, Your Honor.","start":1173.273,"stop":1176.809,"duration":3.54},{"text":"It hasn't gone through rulemaking, formal adjudication and those processes which elevate the amount of deference--","start":1176.809,"stop":1183.878,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's an absolute rule?","start":1183.878,"stop":1184.747,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, it's a little bit contentious on this Court.","start":1184.747,"stop":1189.632,"duration":4.88},{"text":"No, Your Honor, it's a little bit contentious on this Court; but, following Head Products, for example, it wouldn't be entitled to more than Skidmore deference.","start":1189.632,"stop":1200.34,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you answered the argument it shouldn't get any deference because what -- what the EEOC guidance does is it is -- it is interpreting two decisions of this Court, and this Court, not the EEOC, is in the best position to determine what those two cases mean?","start":1200.34,"stop":1219.719,"duration":19.38}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what it is, Your Honor, is it represents an interpretation of the word “ agent ” in Title VII.","start":1219.719,"stop":1225.705,"duration":5.99},{"text":"Now, where -- where the statute -- the statutory term gives off and this Court's interpretation begins is, in some cases, a tough question.","start":1225.705,"stop":1236.763,"duration":11.06},{"text":"But in this case, the EEOC -- the EEOC is really giving definition to the word “ agent ” in Title VII, not so much this Court's interpretations in Faragher and Ellerth.","start":1236.763,"stop":1250.79,"duration":14.03},{"text":"If there are no further questions, Your Honor, I would like to reserve my remaining time for rebuttal.","start":1250.79,"stop":1254.559,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1254.559,"stop":1255.475,"duration":0.92},{"text":"Mr. Srinivasan?","start":1255.475,"stop":1267.132,"duration":11.66}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1267.132,"stop":1269.834,"duration":2.7},{"text":"When a person controls a subordinate's daily work activities and subjects her to harassment, that person qualifies as a supervisor for purposes of the Faragher-Ellerth vicarious liability affirmative defense framework.","start":1269.834,"stop":1281.459,"duration":11.63},{"text":"When it controls daily work activities and, therefore, for example, can compel the cleaning of toilets for a year, the principle that the agency relationship augments the ability to carry out the harassment is implicated in that the victim will lack the same ability to resist the harassment or to report it as would be the case if the harassment were conducted by a coworker that--","start":1281.459,"stop":1301.973,"duration":20.51}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about -- what about the music hypothetical?","start":1301.973,"stop":1304.407,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1304.407,"stop":1305.693,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- where do you think your test comes out on that?","start":1305.693,"stop":1308.728,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it comes out, most likely, against concluding that the person is a supervisor.","start":1308.728,"stop":1314.965,"duration":6.24},{"text":"And the reason is that, under the EEOC enforcement guidance, that accounts for situations in which the authority is exercised over a limited field, a limited number of tasks or assignments.","start":1314.965,"stop":1325.588,"duration":10.62},{"text":"And this is at page 92(a) of the petition appendix.","start":1325.588,"stop":1328.107,"duration":2.52},{"text":"And I think that would qualify under that provision because it's limited.","start":1328.107,"stop":1333.361,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why -- it doesn't really have to do with the number of tasks.","start":1333.361,"stop":1336.046,"duration":2.68},{"text":"It isn't an assignment of tasks.","start":1336.046,"stop":1337.763,"duration":1.72},{"text":"It's something that clearly affects the daily activities of the employee in a way that could be used to implement or facilitate harassment.","start":1337.763,"stop":1349.186,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"It could, Your Honor.","start":1349.186,"stop":1350.222,"duration":1.04},{"text":"I don't disagree with that, and I don't disagree that there are going to be cases that raise issues at the margins.","start":1350.222,"stop":1354.924,"duration":4.7},{"text":"But one way to think about the spectrum of options available to the Court today is to envision that on one end, you have harassment that's perpetrated by a coworker, and you consider the types of harassment that that might entail.","start":1354.924,"stop":1366.732,"duration":11.81},{"text":"And on the other end, you have harassment that's perpetrated by a supervisor with authority over tangible employment actions.","start":1366.732,"stop":1373.636,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and your tests sort of use that, just as you've posed it, as some broad continuum in which we're going to have countless cases trying to figure out whether music falls closer to this end or, you know, what -- the senior employee controls the thermostat, is that closer to this end or that end?","start":1373.636,"stop":1389.728,"duration":16.09},{"text":"Or cutting onions?","start":1389.728,"stop":1391.097,"duration":1.37},{"text":"It seems to me that every single case has its own peculiar facts, and courts are going to be -- have to figure out where on the continuum it resides.","start":1391.097,"stop":1399.453,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, I guess, Your Honor, as Your Honor put it to -- to Petitioner's counsel, the competing approach would be the approach adopted by the Seventh Circuit; but, that approach has some serious flaws.","start":1399.453,"stop":1409.309,"duration":9.86},{"text":"For example, it wouldn't cover the supervisor's conduct that was at issue in Faragher itself, where the supervisor threatened that he would make the harassment victim clean the toilets for a year if she didn't succumb to the harassment.","start":1409.309,"stop":1419.949,"duration":10.64},{"text":"And I think that's a pretty significant cost.","start":1419.949,"stop":1421.966,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't cleaning the toilets a limited -- isn't the authority to decide who cleans the toilets the same as the authority to decide what the music is going to be?","start":1421.966,"stop":1428.02,"duration":6.05},{"text":"It's one thing.","start":1428.02,"stop":1428.888,"duration":0.87},{"text":"I thought -- and your answer on the music was, well, that probably wouldn't count because it's the authority to decide just one thing.","start":1428.888,"stop":1434.959,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we don't -- I guess, we don't know enough about the threat to force her to clean the toilets for a year to know whether it's only one thing.","start":1434.959,"stop":1441.78,"duration":6.82},{"text":"But it could be, for example, that if there -- in the scope of a particular day, you have three particular options as to what you might do, monitor the beach, clean the facilities, including the toilets, or prepare meals, then it's something that covers the entire day.","start":1441.78,"stop":1454.754,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But your argument is if the only authority was to decide who cleans the toilets, then -- then that would not -- that wouldn't count, because that's just one thing.","start":1454.754,"stop":1461.074,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think that -- I don't think we have an answer to that until we know how much of the day's work is encompassed by cleaning the toilets.","start":1461.074,"stop":1470.715,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought in Faragher it was that -- that the lifeguard gave her her daily work assignments.","start":1470.715,"stop":1477.119,"duration":6.4},{"text":"He controlled what she would do on the job.","start":1477.119,"stop":1480.505,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- he controlled every aspect of her -- of her day's work, and cleaning the toilets was one aspect of it.","start":1480.505,"stop":1484.975,"duration":4.47},{"text":"So that was a particularly poignant example that he visited on her as a way to perpetuate the harassment.","start":1484.975,"stop":1489.36,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that can't possibly be what the case means.","start":1489.36,"stop":1491.629,"duration":2.27},{"text":"Suppose that it's -- it's the assignment of offices, and all of the offices except one have heating and air conditioning, but one has no heating and no air conditioning.","start":1491.629,"stop":1500.335,"duration":8.71},{"text":"And so -- and that's the only authority that this person has is to assign desks.","start":1500.335,"stop":1505.721,"duration":5.39},{"text":"That person says, if you don't do whatever it is that I want you to do, I'm putting you in the office where there's no heating, and there's no air conditioning.","start":1505.721,"stop":1512.808,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And you would say that doesn't count because it's just one thing.","start":1512.808,"stop":1516.244,"duration":3.44},{"text":"It's not a broad range of authorities -- of authorities.","start":1516.244,"stop":1519.696,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't constitute authority over daily work activities.","start":1519.696,"stop":1523.898,"duration":4.2},{"text":"And I guess that's what the EEOC guidance authorities--","start":1523.898,"stop":1526.183,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you--","start":1526.183,"stop":1526.583,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--We haven't encountered it in real cases.","start":1526.583,"stop":1528.302,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, you've looked this up.","start":1528.302,"stop":1529.568,"duration":1.27},{"text":"And apparently, for about a dozen years, the EEOC has had, as -- as an alternative basis for qualifying as a supervisor, the individual has authority to direct the employee's daily work activities.","start":1529.568,"stop":1543.227,"duration":13.66},{"text":"And in addition, we have three circuits that for some period of years have been following roughly the same kind of rule.","start":1543.227,"stop":1549.981,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Now, has this problem of the country music or the other problems raised, have they turned out to be a significant problem in those circuits or for the EEOC?","start":1549.981,"stop":1561.856,"duration":11.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"They haven't, Justice Breyer.","start":1561.856,"stop":1563.406,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"They have, or they have not?","start":1563.406,"stop":1564.025,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"They have not.","start":1564.025,"stop":1564.775,"duration":0.75},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1564.775,"stop":1565.225,"duration":0.45},{"text":"They have not turned out to be an issue, and that's what--","start":1565.225,"stop":1567.058,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How do you know that?","start":1567.058,"stop":1567.975,"duration":0.92},{"text":"Are you just saying they have not generated actual Federal -- Federal court reported cases?","start":1567.975,"stop":1573.129,"duration":5.15},{"text":"Do you have any idea how this works on the ground when people complain about the exercise of authority by a coworker who has specific responsibilities that might be reviewed as supervisory?","start":1573.129,"stop":1585.603,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they haven't -- I guess that's two components to the answer, Mr. Chief Justice -- they haven't generated reported or underreported decisions, as far as we've seen.","start":1585.603,"stop":1593.292,"duration":7.69},{"text":"And this is not scientific, and it's just based on our conversations with the EEOC lawyers who are charged with dealing with right to sue letters and the like.","start":1593.292,"stop":1600.648,"duration":7.36},{"text":"They haven't encountered these sorts of situations.","start":1600.648,"stop":1602.914,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The EEOC lawyers think the EEOC plan is working just fine.","start":1602.914,"stop":1605.933,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- I -- I understand that that's not entirely surprising, but--","start":1605.933,"stop":1608.885,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But I guess they'd tell you.","start":1608.885,"stop":1609.218,"duration":0.33},{"text":"There are three who signed the brief, or four.","start":1609.218,"stop":1611.77,"duration":2.55},{"text":"And I guess they'd tell you, wouldn't they--","start":1611.77,"stop":1614.539,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":1614.539,"stop":1614.872,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--what the problems are, if they have problems.","start":1614.872,"stop":1616.824,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1616.824,"stop":1617.358,"duration":0.53},{"text":"In our conversations with them about the way in which these issues arise--","start":1617.358,"stop":1620.21,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, we can ask the other side the same question.","start":1620.21,"stop":1622.495,"duration":2.28},{"text":"They've seen the cases in the circuits.","start":1622.495,"stop":1624.68,"duration":2.19},{"text":"Have they seen instances in the EEOC or before the circuits where it's turned out to be a serious problem, like the country music or any of the other hypotheticals raised?","start":1624.68,"stop":1634.369,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--And I don't think it has, Justice Breyer.","start":1634.369,"stop":1635.885,"duration":1.52},{"text":"And I think it's important to bear in mind that the nature of this inquiry is such that there's going to be cases at the margins that raise difficult questions; but, in Ellerth, the Court recognized that.","start":1635.885,"stop":1644.141,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you how the Seventh Circuit test works in operation?","start":1644.141,"stop":1648.379,"duration":4.24},{"text":"We're in a university setting here, so let me give you a university hypo.","start":1648.379,"stop":1652.931,"duration":4.55},{"text":"There's a professor, and the professor has a secretary.","start":1652.931,"stop":1655.699,"duration":2.77},{"text":"And the professor subjects that secretary to living hell, complete hostile work environment on the basis of sex, all right?","start":1655.699,"stop":1664.139,"duration":8.44},{"text":"But the professor has absolutely no authority to fire the secretary.","start":1664.139,"stop":1667.923,"duration":3.78},{"text":"What would the Seventh Circuit say about that situation?","start":1667.923,"stop":1671.577,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"That if there's no authority over -- to -- to direct annual employment actions, then--","start":1671.577,"stop":1676.612,"duration":5.04}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, the secretary is fired by the head of secretarial services.","start":1676.612,"stop":1678.998,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Professors don't have the ability to fire secretaries; but, professors do have the ability to make secretarial lives living hells.","start":1678.998,"stop":1686.254,"duration":7.26},{"text":"So what does the Seventh Circuit say about that?","start":1686.254,"stop":1688.787,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--The professor would not qualify as a supervisor for purposes of Ellerth-Faragher framework.","start":1688.787,"stop":1693.491,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the Seventh Circuit test.","start":1693.491,"stop":1694.091,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"And so you'd look at it as a -- you'd look at the professor as a coworker, and you'd apply the same standards that applied to harassment conducted by the coworker.","start":1694.091,"stop":1699.645,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though, of course, it's actually more difficult for the secretary to complain about the professor than it would be for the secretary to complain about the head of secretarial services.","start":1699.645,"stop":1709.183,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1709.183,"stop":1709.734,"duration":0.55},{"text":"And I think that's a useful frame of reference that I was trying to articulate earlier, which is that we can envision the cases as falling on a spectrum between ability to complain when the harassment is perpetrated by a coworker on the one hand, and ability to complain when harassment is perpetrated by a supervisor with tangible employment authority--","start":1709.734,"stop":1724.177,"duration":14.44}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"And Mr. Srinivasan, if I can just continue on about this, because I just don't even understand the Seventh Circuit test.","start":1724.177,"stop":1728.997,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Would the Seventh Circuit test also say that -- that that person is not a supervisor even if the professor evaluates the secretary on a yearly basis?","start":1728.997,"stop":1737.437,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--The Seventh Circuit would say that as far as we can tell.","start":1737.437,"stop":1740.472,"duration":3.04},{"text":"They don't appear to have a proviso for circumstances in which the harasser has a role in determining tangible employment actions, because that is one thing that the EEOC guidance takes account of.","start":1740.472,"stop":1752.196,"duration":11.72},{"text":"It's that -- not just that somebody counts as a supervisor when they themselves undertake tangible employment action, but if they have a substantial role in making recommendations that in turn trigger tangible employment actions, the EEOC would take the position that that qualifies.","start":1752.196,"stop":1764.67,"duration":12.47},{"text":"Now, that's not an issue in this case, but that's--","start":1764.67,"stop":1766.206,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You've -- you've talked several times about this going along the spectrum.","start":1766.206,"stop":1769.574,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Where -- where are we supposed to cut off the -- where's the cutting line in the spectrum?","start":1769.574,"stop":1775.312,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think that the -- control over daily work activities is where we would draw the line.","start":1775.312,"stop":1778.514,"duration":3.2},{"text":"And that's what has come up the most in the cases.","start":1778.514,"stop":1781.899,"duration":3.38},{"text":"The reported decisions have conflicts on -- have a conflict on that issue, and that is where the EEOC guidance draws the line.","start":1781.899,"stop":1787.036,"duration":5.14},{"text":"Now, I think it would be helpful, if the Court were going to issue an opinion that adopts that line, to elaborate on -- on that line a little bit in the following sense: That relaying instructions that are -- that are disseminated by one person wouldn't count for those purposes.","start":1787.036,"stop":1803.045,"duration":16.01},{"text":"That's in the EEOC guidance.","start":1803.045,"stop":1804.997,"duration":1.95},{"text":"And -- and it's the functions of a job that actually matter, not the job title.","start":1804.997,"stop":1810.235,"duration":5.24},{"text":"That is also in the EEOC guidance.","start":1810.235,"stop":1811.785,"duration":1.55},{"text":"So I think there are some aspects of the EEOC guidance that elaborate on that line about control over daily activities that I think I would commend to the Court, that it might well--","start":1811.785,"stop":1819.924,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do we have a developed record enough to do that in this case?","start":1819.924,"stop":1822.626,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":1822.626,"stop":1823.159,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I didn't hear you.","start":1823.159,"stop":1823.776,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do -- do we have a developed record enough?","start":1823.776,"stop":1825.745,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Petitioner's counsel says we don't, that the Seventh Circuit test didn't permit them to develop the record sufficiently to clarify all of these issues.","start":1825.745,"stop":1837.385,"duration":11.64},{"text":"We certainly have snippets or -- or lack snippets, as the case may be.","start":1837.385,"stop":1841.77,"duration":4.38},{"text":"But is the record sufficiently developed for the Court to even pronounce -- make pronouncements of that nature?","start":1841.77,"stop":1848.258,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- I think the real question, Justice Sotomayor, is whether the parties had a sufficient opportunity to develop the record.","start":1848.258,"stop":1853.728,"duration":5.47},{"text":"Because if you take the record in the case as a given, we think that the record would support the grant of summary judgment for Ball State University, because there isn't a sufficient showing in the record if you take it as a given that the relevant supervisory -- the relevant putative supervisory employee, Davis, has control over day-to-day work activities.","start":1853.728,"stop":1872.225,"duration":18.5},{"text":"The question that remains is whether the record should be allowed to be expanded.","start":1872.225,"stop":1875.26,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The conclusion in your brief is that the judgment of the court of appeals should be vacated and the case remanded for further proceedings, and now -- now you are telling us that we should -- we should basically write an opinion on summary judgment.","start":1875.26,"stop":1886.866,"duration":11.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sri Srinivasan","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1886.866,"stop":1888.366,"duration":1.5},{"text":"I think if you take the record as a given, that a grant of summary judgment in favor of the employer would be in order.","start":1888.366,"stop":1893.353,"duration":4.99},{"text":"But in the normal course what this Court does when it announces a new standard is it remands for the lower courts to deal with the application of the standard to the facts.","start":1893.353,"stop":1901.19,"duration":7.84},{"text":"And the conclusion in our brief is just, I think, a parroting of that normal conclusion.","start":1901.19,"stop":1904.911,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1904.911,"stop":1906.878,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Mr. Garre.","start":1906.878,"stop":1912.081,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1912.081,"stop":1914.699,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The judgment of the court of appeals should be affirmed because the record establishes that the only employees whose status is at issue lacked the supervisory authority necessary to trigger vicarious liability under Title VII.","start":1914.699,"stop":1928.193,"duration":13.49}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We took this case to decide whether the Faragher and Ellerth -- and Ellerth supervisory liability rule is limited to those harassers who have the power to hire, fire, demote, promote, transfer, or discipline their victim.","start":1928.193,"stop":1942.001,"duration":13.81},{"text":"And your answer to that is no; is that right?","start":1942.001,"stop":1944.719,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1944.719,"stop":1945.769,"duration":1.05},{"text":"We don't think the Seventh Circuit test is the complete answer to the question of who may qualify as a supervisor.","start":1945.769,"stop":1951.039,"duration":5.27},{"text":"But we think it's clear that the -- the person whose status is at issue did not qualify and therefore, the judgment should be affirmed.","start":1951.039,"stop":1957.426,"duration":6.39},{"text":"This Court--","start":1957.426,"stop":1957.795,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1957.795,"stop":1958.178,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Well, if we -- if we agree with that without having any party defending the rule that was adopted by three circuits, then surely -- well, then, why shouldn't we just remand this case for the lower courts to decide this, this summary judgment issue, and -- and permit further development of the record if the record isn't fully developed?","start":1958.178,"stop":1979.042,"duration":20.86}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, most importantly, Justice Alito, because the courts need guidance on how to apply the EEOC and the Second Circuit standard.","start":1979.042,"stop":1986.046,"duration":7},{"text":"The best way to provide that guidance is to do what this Court often does, which is to apply the facts to the standard.","start":1986.046,"stop":1993.218,"duration":7.17},{"text":"In this case, applying the record facts to the standard that we think applies, the “ materially enables the harassment ” standard, it's clear that Ms. Davis, the person who is at issue, does not qualify as a supervisor.","start":1993.218,"stop":2007.109,"duration":13.89},{"text":"And the reason why it's clear is the record is uncontradicted that either the chef or Mr. Kimes made the daily assignments through the prep sheets.","start":2007.109,"stop":2015.549,"duration":8.44},{"text":"The prep sheets are what every employee in the kitchen got each day and they would tell you: Dice vegetables for 60 people; prepare boxed lunches for 20; prepare six vegetable trays.","start":2015.549,"stop":2025.607,"duration":10.06},{"text":"That's -- that was their daily assignments, and the record is absolutely clear, JA 2 -- 277, 278, JA 424 -- that all the employees got the prep sheets from the chef or Mr. Kimes.","start":2025.607,"stop":2038.247,"duration":12.64},{"text":"It's also absolutely clear that Mr. Kimes was the one who controlled the schedule in the kitchen.","start":2038.247,"stop":2043.984,"duration":5.74},{"text":"He is the one that told employees what times of days that they could work.","start":2043.984,"stop":2048.436,"duration":4.45},{"text":"He controlled the schedule.","start":2048.436,"stop":2049.488,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand Mr. Ortiz to say that there's at least a dispute of fact about whether Davis could have controlled what Petitioner did on a daily basis.","start":2049.488,"stop":2059.994,"duration":10.51}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"There is -- there is neither a material nor genuine dispute on that, Your Honor.","start":2059.994,"stop":2064.398,"duration":4.4},{"text":"It at the very--","start":2064.398,"stop":2066.082,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn't her job description say that she can assign tasks in the kitchen?","start":2066.082,"stop":2069.1,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--But they -- they omit the -- the clause that follows, which is critical, which is","start":2069.1,"stop":2073.753,"duration":4.65},{"text":"\"via demonstration, coaching, or overseeing to ensure efficiency. \"","start":2073.753,"stop":2078.372,"duration":4.62},{"text":"That is on page Joint Appendix 13.","start":2078.372,"stop":2080.657,"duration":2.29},{"text":"And that job description has to be read in light of the record that makes crystal clear that it was the chef who did the daily assignments for the prep sheets.","start":2080.657,"stop":2087.93,"duration":7.27},{"text":"And there -- and there are examples of the prep sheets as an exhibit to Ms. Fultz's affidavit, the affidavits at 424 of the Joint Appendix.","start":2087.93,"stop":2095.684,"duration":7.75},{"text":"The -- the exhibits are LLL and JJJ--","start":2095.684,"stop":2099.905,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"We didn't take this case to -- to decide those factual questions.","start":2099.905,"stop":2103.457,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, you--","start":2103.457,"stop":2104.057,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"We really didn't.","start":2104.057,"stop":2105.14,"duration":1.08},{"text":"We took it principally to decide whether the Seventh Circuit rule was -- was right or not.","start":2105.14,"stop":2111.627,"duration":6.49},{"text":"And you don't even defend that.","start":2111.627,"stop":2113.413,"duration":1.79},{"text":"So there is nobody here defending the Seventh Circuit.","start":2113.413,"stop":2115.563,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor has excellent briefing defending the Seventh Circuit.","start":2115.563,"stop":2119.067,"duration":3.5},{"text":"The Chamber of Commerce and other amici have defended it.","start":2119.067,"stop":2121.267,"duration":2.2},{"text":"We certainly think that it -- that -- that it's a superior--","start":2121.267,"stop":2124.369,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They are not talking to us here, are they?","start":2124.369,"stop":2125.553,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, Your Honor.","start":2125.553,"stop":2127.203,"duration":1.65},{"text":"We think it's a superior bright line, but, as we say in our brief, we think that ultimately this Court's precedents compel that the Court reject that.","start":2127.203,"stop":2135.509,"duration":8.31},{"text":"And I think most -- most squarely we look at the Faragher decision.","start":2135.509,"stop":2139.211,"duration":3.7},{"text":"We look at lifeguard Silverman in Faragher, who had the authority to control all aspects of the victim's schedule and daily activities in a virtually unchecked manner.","start":2139.211,"stop":2151.002,"duration":11.79},{"text":"So if the Court is looking for an example that it wants to point to of someone who could qualify under the non-Seventh Circuit category, we think that lifeguard Silverman, from this Court's precedents, would be the example that this Court would hold out.","start":2151.002,"stop":2162.81,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that -- that question wasn't presented.","start":2162.81,"stop":2164.512,"duration":1.7},{"text":"It was -- it was just assumed that -- that Silverman would qualify as a -- as a supervisor.","start":2164.512,"stop":2172.451,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that's absolutely right, Justice Ginsburg.","start":2172.451,"stop":2174.986,"duration":2.53},{"text":"And I think, for some of the reasons that Justice Kagan brought up in her colloquy with -- with Mr. Srinivasan, I think the logic of the Court's precedents, agency principles adopted, would lead to the conclusion that someone who does control virtually all aspects of one's schedule but yet lacks the authority to hire, fire, or demote, nevertheless still would be qualified as someone who--","start":2174.986,"stop":2196.567,"duration":21.58}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Every -- every time -- every time you adopt a rule rather than a multifactor analysis, there are going to be particular cases that fall outside the rule that look like a harsh result.","start":2196.567,"stop":2208.89,"duration":12.32},{"text":"Now, here it simply affects the nature.","start":2208.89,"stop":2210.992,"duration":2.1},{"text":"It doesn't give any immunity for harassment, it just affects the nature of the showing that might be made.","start":2210.992,"stop":2216.111,"duration":5.12},{"text":"You have no difficulty, as representing an employer, by saying that in every case an allegation of this sort is made you have to go through a case-by-case description of the particular responsibilities, whether it's the thermostat, whether it's the music, whether it's the assignment of everything that the employee does, and decide on that basis whether or not you should compensate the victim, or -- or whether or not you should go to court?","start":2216.111,"stop":2245.064,"duration":28.95}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--We do have great difficulty, Your Honor.","start":2245.064,"stop":2248,"duration":2.94},{"text":"First of all, if we are wrong about what this Court's precedents compel, then this Court should adopt the Seventh Circuit principle, and we've -- we've said that in our brief, if we're wrong in our understanding of the Court's precedents.","start":2248,"stop":2257.188,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Secondly, we think that the -- the Court can and should establish meaningful limits on what this broader category of supervisors would require, and I think the case law illustrates that.","start":2257.188,"stop":2267.579,"duration":10.39},{"text":"If you look at the leading circuits who apply the standard--","start":2267.579,"stop":2270.031,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think -- I think your friend on the other side was -- made a good point in his reply brief, which is the variety of circumstances you think courts should look at just happen to correspond with the factual issues that you would have resolved in your favor.","start":2270.031,"stop":2283.256,"duration":13.22}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I -- I would take issue with that.","start":2283.256,"stop":2285.125,"duration":1.87},{"text":"We -- we tried to provide guideposts that would be helpful.","start":2285.125,"stop":2287.16,"duration":2.03},{"text":"But if you look at, for example, the principle that the EEOC agrees with, which -- which is just that limited or marginal occasion authority to lead or oversee by virtue of a paper title, its grade, or seniority is not sufficient.","start":2287.16,"stop":2300.9,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"What does that have to do with agency?","start":2300.9,"stop":2302.419,"duration":1.52},{"text":"That's what I don't understand.","start":2302.419,"stop":2303.502,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Why -- why do any of these tests have to do with agency?","start":2303.502,"stop":2306.288,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor--","start":2306.288,"stop":2307.088,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, I can understand Congress writing a statute that says, you know, any -- any person given -- given authority by the employer, which authority is used to make it more difficult for a person to complain about racial or sexual harassment, is bad.","start":2307.088,"stop":2325.016,"duration":17.93},{"text":"But the statute doesn't say that.","start":2325.016,"stop":2326.368,"duration":1.35},{"text":"It says apply agency principles.","start":2326.368,"stop":2328.052,"duration":1.68},{"text":"How does agency have anything to do with the line you're arguing that we take here?","start":2328.052,"stop":2333.355,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--What this Court said in Faragher and Ellerth -- and I appreciate that you dissented in the case, but what this Court said was it adopted section 219(2)(d) of the Restatement, Second, of Agency, the notion that if -- if there was -- if the employee was aided in the accomplishment of the harassment by virtue of an agency relation, that that would be the agency trigger for liability.","start":2333.355,"stop":2356.054,"duration":22.7}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Then why not leave it there?","start":2356.054,"stop":2356.22,"duration":0.17},{"text":"If that's what the agency is--","start":2356.22,"stop":2358.004,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And RMA then--","start":2358.004,"stop":2360.272,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--then you don't need it at all.","start":2360.272,"stop":2361.022,"duration":0.75},{"text":"So the music -- the music would -- the thermostat would qualify.","start":2361.022,"stop":2364.541,"duration":3.52},{"text":"It would all qualify.","start":2364.541,"stop":2365.01,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think it would, Your Honor, because we agree, certainly, with the EEOC that there are material limits to how far that principle could be stretched.","start":2365.01,"stop":2371.329,"duration":6.32},{"text":"The Court in Ellerth made clear that there were limits to the vicarious liability of employers in this context.","start":2371.329,"stop":2377.333,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":2377.333,"stop":2377.667,"duration":0.33},{"text":"I mean, if that's your principle, apply the principle.","start":2377.667,"stop":2381.185,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for the very--","start":2381.185,"stop":2381.469,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"If you are aided, you know, you're going to work in a cold room unless you, you know, comply with my sexual advances, apply the principle.","start":2381.469,"stop":2388.708,"duration":7.24},{"text":"What's so hard about that?","start":2388.708,"stop":2389.791,"duration":1.08},{"text":"That's a clear line.","start":2389.791,"stop":2391.141,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--This is the balance I think that the Court struck in Ellerth, Your Honor, which was -- it took into account that the statute was passed against the backdrop of agency principles; but, yet, Congress also was cognizant that imposing vicarious liability on the employer for acts that the Court recognized were not themselves authorized by the employer, that that was a punitive aspect of that, and the Court would establish limits.","start":2391.141,"stop":2413.323,"duration":22.18},{"text":"And I think our position takes into account that there have to be limits in this area, on the extent of vicarious liability, in order to give effect to Congress's intent; but, also recognizes, in the situation like you had with the lifeguard in Faragher, that that person did have authority that would assist in the harassment -- they made her clean the toilets, as the lifeguard in Faragher said.","start":2413.323,"stop":2436.106,"duration":22.78},{"text":"And so the Court, I think, struck a reasonable balance.","start":2436.106,"stop":2439.224,"duration":3.12},{"text":"And taking the balance and what this Court said, we think the proper way to resolve this case is to adopt something like the EEOC rule or the Second Circuit rule, but to make clear there are limits.","start":2439.224,"stop":2448.93,"duration":9.71},{"text":"And the best way to make clear that there are limits is to make clear that on the record in this case Ms. Davis did not qualify as a supervisor.","start":2448.93,"stop":2456.769,"duration":7.84},{"text":"Now, my friend said they didn't have the opportunity to develop evidence to the contrary; but, the fact is, from the outset, they litigated this case as if the Seventh Circuit standard did not apply.","start":2456.769,"stop":2465.808,"duration":9.04},{"text":"The reasons that they gave for why Ms. Davis was a supervisor, in the lower court, was that, one, they pointed to the job description, that she had this other authority to “ lead and direct ”, and they also pointed to the fact that she didn't clock in.","start":2465.808,"stop":2477.849,"duration":12.04},{"text":"Those are irrelevant under the Seventh Circuit test.","start":2477.849,"stop":2480.218,"duration":2.37},{"text":"So all along, they had in their mind that they wanted to try to show that Davis was different, and it did have some marginal authority to lead--","start":2480.218,"stop":2487.122,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What guidance would your -- what guidance would the kind of opinion that you're suggesting we write really provide?","start":2487.122,"stop":2492.275,"duration":5.15},{"text":"The -- the guidance would be that if someone has no authority to assign daily work, then that person isn't -- and also has no authority to hire, fire, promote, et cetera, then that person isn't a supervisor.","start":2492.275,"stop":2504.333,"duration":12.06},{"text":"How much guidance is that?","start":2504.333,"stop":2505.2,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it's a lot of guidance, Justice Alito.","start":2505.2,"stop":2508.035,"duration":2.84},{"text":"I think that the flip side of that is the Court would make clear that merely having some occasional or marginal authority to lead or direct by virtue of one's better paper title or seniority is not sufficient to trigger vicarious liability.","start":2508.035,"stop":2521.01,"duration":12.98},{"text":"I think that's going to resolve the mine-run of the cases in which this question has come up and been litigated, at least to the courts of appeals.","start":2521.01,"stop":2527.247,"duration":6.24},{"text":"If you look, for example, at the difference between something like the Mack case out of the Second Circuit and the Mikels case out of the Fourth Circuit, in Mikels, we had an example of two police officers, one had a higher paper rank, corporal versus private, and it was alleged that the corporal was a supervisor.","start":2527.247,"stop":2543.058,"duration":15.81},{"text":"And the court said, no, no, no, he's not a supervisor, all there is, is some marginal occasional authority.","start":2543.058,"stop":2548.195,"duration":5.14},{"text":"That's not sufficient.","start":2548.195,"stop":2549.379,"duration":1.18},{"text":"It was clear that the victim in that case wasn't shy about telling the harasser where to go, to tell him off.","start":2549.379,"stop":2554.766,"duration":5.39},{"text":"And that's the kind of--","start":2554.766,"stop":2556.349,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But why should that -- why should that matter?","start":2556.349,"stop":2558.301,"duration":1.95},{"text":"I know you said that in your brief, Mr. Garre, if the alleged victim talked back.","start":2558.301,"stop":2565.455,"duration":7.15},{"text":"But in one of the very first cases that we had in this line, Harris v. Forklift, there was -- it was the boss, so there was no question about supervisor, and he was really making things hard for this employee; but, she was very firm, and she talked back to him.","start":2565.455,"stop":2585.368,"duration":19.91},{"text":"But, still, that's not what we said that counted.","start":2585.368,"stop":2588.403,"duration":3.03},{"text":"We said, is she being subjected to terms and conditions of employment that she would not be subjected to but for her sex.","start":2588.403,"stop":2597.859,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":2597.859,"stop":2598.676,"duration":0.82},{"text":"And we -- we don't think that that's a dispositive criterion.","start":2598.676,"stop":2601.294,"duration":2.62},{"text":"We recognize the point that the person gets to establish superior ability to stand up to despicable treatment.","start":2601.294,"stop":2607.532,"duration":6.24},{"text":"But I think what our point is, is that it's part of the equation that you would look at.","start":2607.532,"stop":2611.936,"duration":4.4},{"text":"In essence, did the person treat the alleged harasser like a co-employee, or did the person treat the alleged harasser like a supervisor?","start":2611.936,"stop":2620.173,"duration":8.24},{"text":"And in this case, the record is clear that she treated her like a co-employee, someone who -- they obviously had disagreements among them.","start":2620.173,"stop":2627.961,"duration":7.79},{"text":"And I think that's what we take this piece of evidence to assist the Court on the question presented.","start":2627.961,"stop":2633.432,"duration":5.47},{"text":"I think -- but we think what was sufficient to resolve the question presented is the clear and unrefuted evidence that the prep sheets, the daily activities were assigned by the chef or Mr. Kimes, that Mr. Kimes had the authority to control the schedule.","start":2633.432,"stop":2647.192,"duration":13.76},{"text":"And if you want to go further than that, the record also shows that Mr. Kimes had the authority to review -- to do annual reviews.","start":2647.192,"stop":2655.446,"duration":8.25},{"text":"Mr. Kimes had the authority to evaluate.","start":2655.446,"stop":2658.731,"duration":3.29},{"text":"He had all the kind of authority that one would expect in a supervisor.","start":2658.731,"stop":2662.1,"duration":3.37},{"text":"So you would ask the question, what's left?","start":2662.1,"stop":2664.552,"duration":2.45},{"text":"Essentially nothing.","start":2664.552,"stop":2666.018,"duration":1.47},{"text":"And whatever is left, we agree with the EEOC, is not, as a matter of law, sufficient to trigger vicarious liability.","start":2666.018,"stop":2673.324,"duration":7.31},{"text":"That doesn't mean she can't present her claim.","start":2673.324,"stop":2674.941,"duration":1.62},{"text":"It -- it means that it's just simply analyzed under the framework for co-workers, in which she bears the burden of establishing that the employer was negligent in not responding to it.","start":2674.941,"stop":2684.446,"duration":9.51},{"text":"And as Judge Wood, for the court of appeals, and Judge Barker made clear in their detailed opinions, this was not a situation where the employer stuck its head in the sand and ignored incidents of unpleasantries or, in some cases, despicable racial epithets--","start":2684.446,"stop":2698.356,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If you were willing to concede that this would be a close case under the Second Circuit standard or under the EEOC guidance, then there might be an argument in favor of our applying those tests -- or one of those tests to the facts of the case, because then that might provide some guidance, even though we are supposed to be a court of review, not a court of first view.","start":2698.356,"stop":2725.84,"duration":27.48},{"text":"But you're saying this is an extremely weak case under those standards; and, therefore, what is -- what benefit is there in our applying this?","start":2725.84,"stop":2735.898,"duration":10.06},{"text":"Just send it back and have it done in the normal course by the court of appeals or by the district court.","start":2735.898,"stop":2741.468,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, we don't think it's a close case, but my friend does, and his amici do.","start":2741.468,"stop":2745.837,"duration":4.37},{"text":"And I think the damaging signal that this Court would send by remanding on this record would be that, whatever it might say in its opinion, that would have virtually no force in terms of establishing a standard that made clear that this -- whatever else may be true about what would qualify, something like this does not qualify.","start":2745.837,"stop":2764.398,"duration":18.56},{"text":"And, again, like this Court did in the Global Tech case, when the Court establishes a standard, oftentimes, it applies the standard to the facts and appreciates that that's the best way, the most judicial way of providing guidance on what that standard means.","start":2764.398,"stop":2778.741,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Garre, there is one BSU internal document that -- a note to the file by a compliance officer, who apparently investigated one of the complaints, that says that -- Kimes is recorded as saying -- he's the avowed supervisor -- that he, quote,","start":2778.741,"stop":2798.821,"duration":20.08},{"text":"\"knows Davis has given direction to Vance, and that he just doesn't know what else to do. \"","start":2798.821,"stop":2804.975,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Doesn't that defeat summary judgment on its face?","start":2804.975,"stop":2808.946,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't, Your Honor, if you agree with our principle, that the EEOC also agrees with, that having some limited or marginal authority to lead or direct as a matter of law is not sufficient.","start":2808.946,"stop":2820.235,"duration":11.29},{"text":"So that that piece of evidence, even in its reasonable inference, would not be sufficient to create a material issue.","start":2820.235,"stop":2825.472,"duration":5.24},{"text":"It also wouldn't be sufficient creating -- looking at the body of the evidence, which makes crystal clear that the prep sheets are really what was driving the daily activities in this workplace.","start":2825.472,"stop":2835.514,"duration":10.04},{"text":"And it was Kimes or the chef that did the prep sheets, not Ms. Davis at all.","start":2835.514,"stop":2840.398,"duration":4.88},{"text":"And it -- and it was also not material in light of the evidence that Mr. Kimes did the schedule.","start":2840.398,"stop":2845.035,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Ms. Davis was asked at her deposition on page 135, quote, “ Was there ever ” --","start":2845.035,"stop":2851.523,"duration":6.49},{"text":"\"have you ever been assigned to a less meaningful or fulfilling job classification? \"","start":2851.523,"stop":2855.725,"duration":4.2},{"text":"And her response was yes, and she pointed to an example by Mr. Kimes, because it was Mr. Kimes who had the authority to make those assignments, not Ms. Davis.","start":2855.725,"stop":2864.931,"duration":9.21},{"text":"So the mere fact that you've got some marginal evidence drawn from snippets, giving it a reasonable inference that she at times had some ability to lead or direct, as the job description says,","start":2864.931,"stop":2875.805,"duration":10.87},{"text":"\"by coaching, demonstration or overseeing. \"","start":2875.805,"stop":2877.524,"duration":1.72},{"text":"is not sufficient as a matter of law to entitle her to summary judgment, nor do we think that this Court should take the unusual step of remanding so that she can dig into events six years old through new discovery.","start":2877.524,"stop":2888.648,"duration":11.12},{"text":"Again--","start":2888.648,"stop":2889.031,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Garre, could I ask you about that?","start":2889.031,"stop":2890.014,"duration":0.98},{"text":"You said before that there is no -- nothing to suggest that she left anything on the table because of the nature of the Seventh Circuit standard.","start":2890.014,"stop":2898.92,"duration":8.91},{"text":"So what's the best place in the record for us to look to decide that question as to whether she at all didn't present or didn't develop evidence because of the nature of the Seventh Circuit standard?","start":2898.92,"stop":2913.18,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, first, I would look at her summary judgment briefs, Your Honor, and in those briefs she argued that Davis was a supervisor because, one, under the job description she had the authority to lead and direct, the same sorts of things that we are talking now and would be talking about under the EEOC and Second Circuit tests.","start":2913.18,"stop":2929.373,"duration":16.19},{"text":"And, two, she points to the fact that they didn't clock in, again something that is irrelevant under the Seventh Circuit test.","start":2929.373,"stop":2934.593,"duration":5.22},{"text":"So this wasn't a case where the litigant felt themselves bound by the legal standard and one could surmise that they would have pursued it differently.","start":2934.593,"stop":2941.949,"duration":7.36},{"text":"I think I would look at that first.","start":2941.949,"stop":2943.116,"duration":1.17},{"text":"And then I would look at her deposition transcript which is in the Joint Appendix and the three affidavits that she put in, in this case, which are in the Joint Appendix.","start":2943.116,"stop":2951.889,"duration":8.77},{"text":"At some point you would expect her to come along and try to rebut the notion that Mr. Kimes and Ms. Fultz assigned the daily activities through the prep sheets.","start":2951.889,"stop":2962.696,"duration":10.81},{"text":"In fact, it's just the contrary.","start":2962.696,"stop":2964.596,"duration":1.9},{"text":"If anything, in her own affidavit she seems to accept that the prep sheets were done by Kimes and the chef.","start":2964.596,"stop":2970.283,"duration":5.69},{"text":"That's at JA 430.","start":2970.283,"stop":2971.718,"duration":1.43},{"text":"You would expect her to contest the notion that Mr. Kimes was the one who did the scheduling, who did her annual reviews, who disciplined her on occasion.","start":2971.718,"stop":2980.408,"duration":8.69},{"text":"After all, she was claiming that Davis was the supervisor, and she didn't feel bound by the Seventh Circuit tests.","start":2980.408,"stop":2985.626,"duration":5.22},{"text":"So you would expect to see some indication of how Ms. Davis actually assigned her something to do, changed her schedule, the like.","start":2985.626,"stop":2994.232,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Instead what you find is all those sorts of allegations, she made them, but all those sorts of allegations were directed to Mr. Kimes.","start":2994.232,"stop":3001.321,"duration":7.09},{"text":"That was the basis for her retaliation claim, which isn't before the Court.","start":3001.321,"stop":3004.689,"duration":3.37},{"text":"But there are all the sorts of things that you might expect one to complain about against a supervisor in this sort of vein: She made me cut vegetables instead of doing the baking like I like to do; she didn't assign me enough overtime so I could make more money; she changed my hours.","start":3004.689,"stop":3021.199,"duration":16.51},{"text":"Those allegations were made.","start":3021.199,"stop":3022.668,"duration":1.47},{"text":"They were directed at Mr. Kimes and that's perfectly consistent with the record evidence.","start":3022.668,"stop":3026.703,"duration":4.03},{"text":"There was Kimes and the chef who had the authority to do her daily activities, and Kimes had the authority to do the schedule.","start":3026.703,"stop":3033.107,"duration":6.4},{"text":"It's not enough for her to come here today, I don't think, and just speculate that having an opportunity to go through greater discovery, which in essence would amount to a fishing expedition, the Court should take the unusual step of remanding to give her an opportunity for discovery.","start":3033.107,"stop":3049.302,"duration":16.2},{"text":"This Court -- although we acknowledge oftentimes this Court does remand for the lower courts to undertake that inquiry, it certainly doesn't always do so.","start":3049.302,"stop":3057.408,"duration":8.11},{"text":"So Global-Tech is one example; we've cited many more in our briefs.","start":3057.408,"stop":3060.36,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And here, I think, again, the parties -- there is broad agreement on what the standard should be.","start":3060.36,"stop":3066.43,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Something like the EEOC or Second Circuit test is, we think, the best way to frame it.","start":3066.43,"stop":3070.632,"duration":4.2},{"text":"But given the debate among the parties about what that test means and how it applies to Davis here, I think it's absolutely critical for the Court to apply the legal test to the record facts and hold that Ms. Davis is not a supervisor and to affirm the judgment below.","start":3070.632,"stop":3086.76,"duration":16.13},{"text":"Although it's not before this Court, if one wants to go to the next step and think about the affirmative defenses and the like, this isn't a case where the Court would be putting to rest a valid Title VII claim.","start":3086.76,"stop":3097.533,"duration":10.77},{"text":"But the claim was extensively looked at below by Judge Barker in the district court, Judge Wood and her colleagues on the court of appeals, and they found an environment in which Ball State reacted responsibly to the allegations that were made, investigated them and took prompt action where the investigation warranted it, particularly with respect to the most despicable things that were uncovered, racial epithets that were used by another employee, Ms. McVicker, not Ms. Davis.","start":3097.533,"stop":3123.783,"duration":26.25},{"text":"The only allegations against Ms. Davis that we think are relevant here during the time period that Ms. Davis was a part-time employee were: One, the so-called elevator incident where Ms. Davis allegedly blocked Ms. Vance as she got out of the elevator, which isn't race-based at all, we don't think; and two, the alleged use of words like “ Sambo ” or “ Buckwheat ” to refer--","start":3123.783,"stop":3146.799,"duration":23.02}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ortiz said it wasn't just part-time.","start":3146.799,"stop":3148.834,"duration":2.03},{"text":"He called my attention to the page before that says she also -- that Davis also directed--","start":3148.834,"stop":3158.274,"duration":9.44}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, we disagree with that, Your Honor.","start":3158.274,"stop":3162.909,"duration":4.64},{"text":"If you look on page JA 12, the job description position function, the last sentence says","start":3162.909,"stop":3168.545,"duration":5.64},{"text":"\"Requires leadership of up to 20 part-time substitute and student employees. \"","start":3168.545,"stop":3172.366,"duration":3.82},{"text":"So we think it's clear.","start":3172.366,"stop":3173.049,"duration":0.68},{"text":"We said this is in our red brief and there wasn't any response to it in the yellow brief, that any authority, any conceivable supervisory authority, could have only existed when Ms. Vance was a part-time employee.","start":3173.049,"stop":3185.591,"duration":12.54},{"text":"But we don't think that that's relevant, Your Honor, because putting aside whether she had authority over catering assistants who were part time or full time, the record is absolutely clear that Ms. Davis just lacked the authority that would have been sufficient to trigger vicarious liability.","start":3185.591,"stop":3202.219,"duration":16.63},{"text":"And again we think the paradigm case where that authority is present is something like the lifeguard in Silverman where they control all aspects of the daily activities, one's schedule, one's daily work assignments, and down the line.","start":3202.219,"stop":3213.693,"duration":11.47},{"text":"Here there is no evidence that any of that authority that was possessed, and the record makes clear beyond doubt that all that authority was possessed by others, Ms. -- the chef and Mr. Kimes.","start":3213.693,"stop":3225.418,"duration":11.72},{"text":"And I think, as the amicus brief makes clear, this is consistent with workplaces across America today, where jobs are less hierarchical, more collaborative, and so where you have got more senior employees by virtue of their experience or job title, just a paper title, are in a broad sense team leaders of the like in the workplace.","start":3225.418,"stop":3245.396,"duration":19.98},{"text":"That doesn't mean they are supervisors in any traditional sense, and it certainly doesn't mean they are supervisors for purposes of triggering vicarious liability under Title VII.","start":3245.396,"stop":3255.02,"duration":9.62},{"text":"So for those reasons, we would urge this Court to affirm the judgment below, to make clear in order to provide the needed guidance to the courts of appeals and the assumption that something like the EEOC or Second Circuit standard does apply to determine who is a supervisor triggering vicarious liability.","start":3255.02,"stop":3274.565,"duration":19.55},{"text":"Ms. Davis, the only employee who is at issue, does not meet that standard.","start":3274.565,"stop":3278.719,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3278.719,"stop":3281.838,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"If you have no more questions, thank you.","start":3281.838,"stop":3282.671,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ortiz, you have 4 more minutes remaining.","start":3282.671,"stop":3284.688,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":3284.688,"stop":3287.006,"duration":2.32},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit rule is not one that can be justified in terms of its superior judicial manageability, administrability, despite producing a few odd results.","start":3287.006,"stop":3298.781,"duration":11.78},{"text":"As Justice Kagan's question revealed, it produces truly perverse results.","start":3298.781,"stop":3306.369,"duration":7.59},{"text":"Someone who can tell you what to do in your job day-to-day, manage you during the whole job period, what kind of tasks you have to do, was not necessarily considered a supervisor, while the person upstairs in human resources that you may never see or even know would be considered your supervisor.","start":3306.369,"stop":3323.498,"duration":17.13}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you adopted that rule I suppose you could couple it with an increased duty of care on the part of the employer to take necessary steps to prevent forbidden harassment.","start":3323.498,"stop":3339.941,"duration":16.44},{"text":"In other words, you up the duty of care on the part of the employer generally.","start":3339.941,"stop":3343.994,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Kennedy, that in fact is one thing the Seventh Circuit has tried to do, but it dispels any kind of certainty and predictability in the rule, because the duty of care of course would be determined by a jury only after hearing a particular case.","start":3343.994,"stop":3360.271,"duration":16.28},{"text":"Second, my friend tries to get out from under the clear import of the job description here by saying directing and leading somehow don't count because that is accomplished through oversight.","start":3360.271,"stop":3373.598,"duration":13.33},{"text":"Oversight, however, is a common synonym for supervision itself.","start":3373.598,"stop":3378.383,"duration":4.78},{"text":"It's merely a dog chasing its own tail.","start":3378.383,"stop":3381.002,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Third, it's no surprise that many of the things that Ms. Vance referred to, the particular instance she referred to went back to William Kimes.","start":3381.002,"stop":3389.94,"duration":8.94},{"text":"Of course, that related to the retaliation part of her claim, which is not before this Court.","start":3389.94,"stop":3395.761,"duration":5.82},{"text":"Also, Your Honor, Faragher in the end is not a toilet cleaning case.","start":3395.761,"stop":3399.729,"duration":3.97},{"text":"The district court did not find -- made no finding on that.","start":3399.729,"stop":3404.033,"duration":4.3},{"text":"The court of appeals didn't mention it.","start":3404.033,"stop":3406.152,"duration":2.12},{"text":"This Court in its Faragher opinion mentioned only that it was an allegation in the complaint.","start":3406.152,"stop":3410.104,"duration":3.95},{"text":"It is not clear -- the allegation of the complainant was that he said that, not that Silverman actually had that authority.","start":3410.104,"stop":3417.008,"duration":6.9},{"text":"And it was clear from the case that he actually wasn't interested in even dating Faragher, it was just a way of humiliating her in the workplace.","start":3417.008,"stop":3423.863,"duration":6.86},{"text":"So just as Faragher's expressed, it was not clear that was even something that Silverman had authority to do.","start":3423.863,"stop":3429.434,"duration":5.57},{"text":"And finally, if this Court is worried about sending signals, think about what kind of signal it will be sending to litigants in the future if it were to affirm, simply affirm here.","start":3429.434,"stop":3441.242,"duration":11.81},{"text":"In the future, whenever anyone is thinking that they may want to challenge a rule, no matter how well-settled it is in a particular circuit, they would have an incentive to, through discovery, to produce information that might be relevant to any future twist.","start":3441.242,"stop":3458.002,"duration":16.76}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is there any?","start":3458.002,"stop":3458.954,"duration":0.95},{"text":"You said he went through, you weren't preceding on the -- your client, originally in district court, not preceding on the basis of the straight Seventh Circuit test.","start":3458.954,"stop":3468.809,"duration":9.86},{"text":"He had the EEOC look into it; the Government itself says that we should affirm and they have EEOC lawyers on it.","start":3468.809,"stop":3475.963,"duration":7.15},{"text":"And so is there any piece of information that would be relevant that you know of that you would introduce, were it sent back, say to the district court, that you have not already introduced?","start":3475.963,"stop":3487.771,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, first, the Solicitor General's office does not now take the position that affirmance is proper.","start":3487.771,"stop":3493.591,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I read what they said in the last page of their brief.","start":3493.591,"stop":3495.793,"duration":2.2},{"text":"They said either affirm, that was their first thing, or send it back.","start":3495.793,"stop":3499.679,"duration":3.89},{"text":"Okay.","start":3499.679,"stop":3500.281,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Now my question remains the same.","start":3500.281,"stop":3502.481,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3502.481,"stop":3503.483,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there--","start":3503.483,"stop":3504.299,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"There is.","start":3504.299,"stop":3505.116,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--What is it?","start":3505.116,"stop":3506.282,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 197 of the Joint Appendix, in the deposition testimony of Ms. Vance, she says that Davis told her what to do, what not to do.","start":3506.282,"stop":3515.905,"duration":9.62},{"text":"In the internal memo to the file that Justice Sotomayor pointed to, William Kimes, who had the authority--","start":3515.905,"stop":3523.578,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Justice Breyer's question was what's not in the record?","start":3523.578,"stop":3528.112,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"--Oh, what's not -- I'm sorry, Your Honor.","start":3528.112,"stop":3529.481,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you have something that's not in the record that will materially add to this discourse?","start":3529.481,"stop":3535.468,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3535.468,"stop":3536.585,"duration":1.12},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3536.585,"stop":3536.885,"duration":0.3},{"text":"In document number 62-3, which concerns the deposition testimony of another employee -- is not in the Joint Appendix, which -- which -- which is the deposition testimony of another employee named Julie Murphy.","start":3536.885,"stop":3552.228,"duration":15.34},{"text":"Ms. Murphy testified that Davis, quote unquote, gave orders in the kitchen.","start":3552.228,"stop":3558.667,"duration":6.44},{"text":"That's on page 24, I believe.","start":3558.667,"stop":3560.901,"duration":2.23},{"text":"On page 38, she testifies that Davis was understood as a supervisor.","start":3560.901,"stop":3565.905,"duration":5},{"text":"And on page 37, she indicates that she received particular orders from Davis to do different things, like clean a particular piece of kitchen equipment, at different times.","start":3565.905,"stop":3575.193,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's all in the record in this Court.","start":3575.193,"stop":3577.378,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3577.378,"stop":3577.778,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Just not in the Joint Appendix.","start":3577.778,"stop":3578.997,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Daniel R. Ortiz","textObjs":[{"text":"Just not in the Joint Appendix, Your Honor.","start":3578.997,"stop":3579.814,"duration":0.82},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3579.814,"stop":3580.264,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3580.264,"stop":3580.764,"duration":0.5},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3580.764,"stop":3581.58,"duration":0.82}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Nov 26, 2012","petitioner":"Maetta Vance","respondent":"Ball State University","docket":"11-556","citation":"570 US _ (2013)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/570/11-556","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit","grantedOn":"Jun 25, 2012","decidedOn":"Jun 24, 2013"}